      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Race for No. 2: A Debate With a Difference</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stan Horowitz letter, commenting on October 6 article, says debate between Democratic vice presidential nominee Sen Joseph I Lieberman and Republican rival Dick Cheney was refreshing and involved honorable exchange on issues</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Civil Clash, Cheney and Lieberman Reinforce Tickets' Sharp Differences'' (front page, Oct. 6):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Civil Clash, Cheney and Lieberman Reinforce Tickets' Sharp Differences'' (front page, Oct. 6):</p>
        <p>For 90 minutes, America put its best foot forward. Joseph I. Lieberman and Dick Cheney allowed me to forget about Al Gore and George W. Bush. Instead of watching a split-screen debate filled with sighs, head-shaking, scowls and blank stares, I watched an honorable exchange on the issues.</p>
        <p>The slot on a party's ticket for ground-breaking candidates has always been reserved for the vice president: Geraldine A. Ferraro for women, Mr. Lieberman for Jews. But on Thursday night, I saw the ticket take its most prominent risk: highly qualified statesmen debating for the right to lead this great country. It was refreshing.</p>
        <p>STAN HOROWITZ  New York, Oct. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
